Provide a storytelling definition of {concept}.

Write it in plain, emotionally accessible English for people who speak English as
a foreign language.

Start with the first times where {concept} appears in the Bible and
continue through the Bible. Use stories, examples, and vivid
descriptions from the Bible. Highlight its significance in creation,
the Old Testament, the life of Jesus, the Revelation, and any other 
biblical accounts, in chronological order.

If the concept does not appear in certain sections of the Bible, omit
those sections. For instance, the cross occurs only in the New
Testament, so an article about the cross does not contain a section on
the Old Testament.  Do not insert concepts as metaphors in places
where the Bible does not mention the concept.

If {concept} was prophesied or prefigured through types, discuss these
prophecies or types as understood at the time, and withhold the
fulfilment until the appropriate time.  For instance, an article on
Jesus should discuss prophecies of the Messiah in the Old Testament,
and explain how they are fulfilled later, when discussing the life of
Jesus.

Focus on what is clearly expressed in the Bible and avoid speculative
interpretations. Make the definition accessible to oral cultures by
using simple, clear language and repetition.

If {concept} is a physical item, start by describing it to help people
visualize it as though they were close to the item, focusing on the
most salient characteristics.

Focus on storytelling: Use stories, examples, or anecdotes to
introduce and explain key concepts. Oral cultures often prefer
learning through narratives rather than abstract explanations.

Simple and clear language: Use simple but respectful language. Avoid
jargon, technical terms, or overly complex sentence structures. Ensure
the text flows naturally, almost as if being spoken aloud.

Engage with cultural references: Where appropriate, incorporate
culturally familiar symbols, metaphors, or examples. Keep in mind that
specific cultural sensitivities may vary, so keep the language
universally relatable.

Sequential structure: Organize information in a clear, logical
sequence. Oral cultures often appreciate content delivered
step-by-step, moving naturally from one idea to the next.

Incorporate dialogue: Use conversational elements like imagined
dialogue, questions, or direct address to the reader, making the
material feel interactive and engaging.

Visual and sensory descriptions: Appeal to the senses—include vivid
descriptions that evoke visual, auditory, or emotional images to help
bring concepts to life.

